data.content:
## What breaks in .NET 11

My training data predates .NET 11, so I can't confirm the exact release notes. However, the known trajectory is clear:

**In .NET 10 (EF Core 10)**, the Cosmos DB provider threw `InvalidOperationException` on synchronous calls by default, but you could opt back in:

```csharp
options.UseCosmos(..., o => o.AllowSynchronousIO());
```

**In .NET 11 (EF Core 11)**, that opt-in is expected to be **removed entirely**. All four of your methods will throw `InvalidOperationException` at runtime — there's no workaround flag anymore.

## The fix: go fully async

```csharp
public class ProductRepository
{
    private readonly CosmosDbContext _context;

    public async Task<List<Product>> GetAllAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.ToListAsync();
    }

    public async Task<Product> GetByIdAsync(int id)
    {
        return await _context.Products.FirstAsync(p => p.Id == id);
    }

    public async Task<int> GetCountAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.CountAsync();
    }

    public async Task SaveAsync(Product product)
    {
        _context.Products.Add(product);
        await _context.SaveChangesAsync();
    }
}
```

**Key changes:**
| Sync call | Async replacement |
|---|---|
| `ToList()` | `await ToListAsync()` |
| `First()` | `await FirstAsync()` |
| `Count()` | `await CountAsync()` |
| `SaveChanges()` | `await SaveChangesAsync()` |

All async LINQ methods live in `Microsoft.EntityFrameworkCore` namespace. You'll also need to propagate `async/await` up through your call chain (controllers, services, etc.).

> **Tip:** Search your codebase for `.ToList()`, `.First(`, `.Count()`, `.SaveChanges()` on any `DbSet` backed by Cosmos to find all call sites that need migration. The relational providers (SQL Server, PostgreSQL, etc.) still support sync — this removal is Cosmos-specific.
